<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Beyond_Freedom_and_Dignity&amp;action=edit&amp;section=17" title="Edit section: Notes">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Notes</span></h2>
<ol class="references">
<li id="cite_note-0"><b><a href="#cite_ref-0" title="">^</a></b> Skinner, B.F. Beyond Freedom and Dignity. page 24 Hardback edition</li>
<li id="cite_note-1"><b><a href="#cite_ref-1" title="">^</a></b> Skinner, B.F. Beyond Freedom and Dignity. p.26</li>
<li id="cite_note-2"><b><a href="#cite_ref-2" title="">^</a></b> ibid p.42</li>
<li id="cite_note-3"><b><a href="#cite_ref-3" title="">^</a></b> Skinner, B.F. Beyond Freedom and Dignity, p. 58 "We recognize a person's dignity or worth when we give him credit for what he has done"</li>
<li id="cite_note-4"><b><a href="#cite_ref-4" title="">^</a></b> ibid p.44</li>
<li id="cite_note-5"><b><a href="#cite_ref-5" title="">^</a></b> "The fundamental mistake made by all those who choose weak methods of control is to assume that the balance of control is left to the individual, when in fact it is left to other conditions." p.99 - Skinner, B.F. Beyond Freedom and Dignity</li>
<li id="cite_note-6"><b><a href="#cite_ref-6" title="">^</a></b> ibid p.100</li>
<li id="cite_note-7"><b><a href="#cite_ref-7" title="">^</a></b> ibid p.101</li>
<li id="cite_note-8"><b><a href="#cite_ref-8" title="">^</a></b> "A technology of behavior is available...but the defenders of freedom oppose its use." Skinner, B.F. Beyond Freedom and Dignity p. 125</li>
<li id="cite_note-9"><b><a href="#cite_ref-9" title="">^</a></b> ibid p.131</li>
<li id="cite_note-10"><b><a href="#cite_ref-10" title="">^</a></b> ibid p.133</li>
<li id="cite_note-11"><b><a href="#cite_ref-11" title="">^</a></b> ibid. 145</li>
<li id="cite_note-12"><b><a href="#cite_ref-12" title="">^</a></b> ibid p.148</li>
<li id="cite_note-13"><b><a href="#cite_ref-13" title="">^</a></b> p.150 "Such a technology is ethically neutral. It can be used by villain or saint." Skinner, B.F. Beyond Freedom and Dignity.</li>
<li id="cite_note-14"><b><a href="#cite_ref-14" title="">^</a></b> Although Skinner mentions Plato, Augustine and was presumably inspired by Bacon's Atlantic and does not explicitly mention Walden Two in this reference. p.153 ibid</li>
<li id="cite_note-15"><b><a href="#cite_ref-15" title="">^</a></b> ibid p.186 aggression, industry, attention are addressed specifically</li>
<li id="cite_note-16"><b><a href="#cite_ref-16" title="">^</a></b> "A great deal goes on inside the organism" ibid. p195</li>
<li id="cite_note-17"><b><a href="#cite_ref-17" title="">^</a></b> Mecca Chiesa's Radical Behaviorism deals with the misunderstanding of Skinner's analysis as "mechanistic" in some detail</li>
<li id="cite_note-18"><b><a href="#cite_ref-18" title="">^</a></b> See e.g. <a href="http://cogsci.umn.edu/millennium/final.html" class="external text" title="http://cogsci.umn.edu/millennium/final.html" rel="nofollow">The one hundred most influential works in cognitive science from the 20th century</a> or Skinner's own ironic acknowledgment of Chomsky's influence in On 'Having' A Poem (<a href="http://www.bfskinner.org/media/Having_a_Poem.ram" class="external text" title="http://www.bfskinner.org/media/Having_a_Poem.ram" rel="nofollow">RealAudio</a>)</li>
<li id="cite_note-19"><b><a href="#cite_ref-19" title="">^</a></b> Chomsky, N. The Case Against B.F.Skinner <a href="http://www.chomsky.info/articles/19711230.htm" class="external free" title="http://www.chomsky.info/articles/19711230.htm" rel="nofollow">http://www.chomsky.info/articles/19711230.htm</a></li>
<li id="cite_note-20"><b><a href="#cite_ref-20" title="">^</a></b> <i>Beyond Freedom and Dignity</i> (New York: Bantam Vintage paperback, 1972), p. 17.</li>
<li id="cite_note-21"><b><a href="#cite_ref-21" title="">^</a></b> <i>Beyond Freedom and Dignity</i> (New York: Bantam Vintage, 1972), pp. 190-191. By "homunculus," Skinner refers to what he would describe as a mistaken view that there is a "little man" inside one's head (a mind, soul, or will). See, for example, <a href="/wiki/Homunculus#Homunculus_argument_or_fallacy_in_the_philosophy_of_mind" title="Homunculus">here</a>.</li>
</ol>


